  "prompt": "What is the speed of electron?",
  "response": "The speed of an electron can vary greatly depending on the context in which it is moving. In different scenarios, electrons can have very different speeds:\n\n1. **In a Vacuum (Free Electron):**  \n   Electrons in a vacuum can be accelerated to very high speeds, close to the speed of light (approximately \\(3 \\times 10^8 \\, \\text{m/s}\\)), especially in particle accelerators.\n\n2. **In a Conductor (Electric Current):**  \n   The **drift velocity** of electrons in a conductor (e.g., in a copper wire) is surprisingly slow, typically on the order of millimeters per second (e.g., \\(10^{-3} \\, \\text{m/s}\\)). However, the electric field in the conductor propagates at nearly the speed of light, causing the effect of current to appear almost instantaneous.\n\n3. **In an Atom (Orbital Motion):**  \n   Electrons in atoms move at extremely high speeds, often on the order of \\(10^6 \\, \\text{m/s}\\), depending on the energy level and the atom.\n\n4. **Thermal Motion:**  \n   In a gas or plasma, electrons move at speeds determined by their thermal energy, which can be calculated using the root mean square (RMS) velocity formula:  \n   \\[\n   v_{\\text{RMS}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3kT}{m}}  \n   \\]  \n   where \\(k\\) is the Boltzmann constant, \\(T\\) is the temperature, and \\(m\\) is the mass of the electron.\n\nIn summary, the speed of an electron depends on the specific situation, ranging from very slow (drift velocity in conductors) to very fast (close to the speed of light in accelerators).",
